Player races
============

The Basics
----------
Player races are not races in the normal sense, but rather racially based
cultures. Each culture is drawn from an in-play area inhabited by that
culture. Not all areas in DarkWind contain cultures that are appropriate
for a player race, nor are all appropriate cultures included in the set
of player races. The minimum criteria for inclusion as a player race
are that:

        1) The race is drawn from an in-play area.
        2) A reasonable population of the race be present in the area.
        3) The area contains a city, camp, or other permanent or
           semi-permanent gathering place for members of that race.

Although player races are drawn from npc areas, players and npc do not
have the same kind of race attribute. Player races are specific to a 
particular culture while npc races are broader groupings along more
traditional racial divides. For example, the player race "high elf" is
drawn from the Elf Kingdom, but the npcs of the kingdom are of the
racial type "elf".

New player races can be added quite easily, and it is expected that over
time the list of available races will grow considerably.


Racial Bonuses
--------------
Races are balanced according to a point-based power allocation scheme.
The point scheme is intended to provide a level of objectivity in
balancing each race against the other. It is probably possible to abuse
the system. Don't do it, it's bad.

Each common race is allowed a total of 100 racial power points worth of
extra powers and characteristics. Common races are available to players
in the Hall of Races on the appropriate continent.

Each exotic race is allowed a total of 125 racial power points. Exotic
races should have a separate race room in the originating area where
players can reincarnate into that race only.

Currently there are the following powers allowed for races:

    Exp bonus:            Bonus to exp gained.
    Stat bonus/penalty:   % bonus/penalty to base stats.
    Alignment tendencies: Bonus to moves towards, penalty to moves away.
    Size:                 Affects relative weapon sizes.
    Dark vision:          Vision in various levels of darkness.
    Magic/Psi resistance: Resist magic, psionics.
    Eat/drink bonus:      Effectively increases capacity and detox/desate.
    Damage resistance:    Damage reduction vs types. (also vulnerability)
    Weapon mastery:       Unaffected by out-of-spec weapon penalties.
    Hyperborean:          Resistance to Hyper cold effect, resist cold,
                          vulnerable to heat.
    Souvraeli:            Resistance to Souv heat dam, resist heat,
                          vulnerable to cold.
    Winged:               Allows wing piercings.
    Flight:               Allows flight.
    Race change:          Allows free race changes.
    Breath weapon:        Allows use of breath player command.
    Damage type:          Extra damage type on attacks.
    SP regen rate:        Increases the base regen rate of sp.
    Languages:            Free (fluent) languages besides common.


Race rooms
----------
Race rooms allow players to describe the races available there and
reincarnate into them. DW, Hyper and Souv have race rooms for common
races from those continents, whereas exotic races have their own race
rooms.


Technical information
---------------------
The guildd.h header contains information on racial guild restrictions.

The race.h header contains most of the information about each race.

The RCOLOR define should be deprecated, but is messy to change over. In
the future, keys that correspond to the old race set should be removed.

The RACE_MAP define contains the details about the new set of races and
their powers. DO NOT access RACE_MAP directly to extract racial
characteristics. Use the function query_race_data() instead. (see the
funhelp for query_race_data() for usage)

